abstract.0: Chatbots and digital assistants are hot and emerging technologies, and best practices are still evolving.  How will real users interact with a chatbot?  What are the differences between chatbots and digital assistants? How to identify the top use cases? How to extract conversational design from LOB stakeholders who may never have interacted with chatbots before? In this session learn how to ensure a successful digital assistant implementation, including how to identify use cases, design top-notch conversational flows, target functionality for your key users, integrate with backend system. Discover the secrets to successful implementations and how you can reap real business benefits.
abstract.1: This session begins by briefly covering the Docker basics and then dives in into the more intermediate use of Docker. This session is aimed database developers who would like to set up a development and/or test environment using a microservices architecture consisting of multiple containers (for example, one container for an Oracle Database, one or more containers to support Oracle REST Data Services, and one or more containers to execute specific NodeJS applications). Setting this up in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Container Service Classic is also discussed.
abstract.2: This session explores .NET coding best practices and optimization techniques to achieve fast Oracle data access performance for both on-premises and in the cloud. Learn tips to improve connection management, statement execution, data fetching, data type use, and caching to boost application performance and scalability. See how to use Oracle Performance Analyzer and SQL Tuning Advisor from within Visual Studio to tune .NET application performance.
abstract.3: Setting up highly available architectures for your Oracle applications such as Oracle E-Business Suite and Oracle’s JD Edwards and PeopleSoft used to be difficult and expensive. But moving them to the cloud—specifically Oracle Cloud Infrastructure—allows you to easily take advantage of the natural redundancies this new IaaS platform offers you. In this session learn how easy it is to deploy your apps in a highly available configuration, distributed across availability domains that are fault tolerant against any imaginable catastrophe and replicated across geographic regions. Learn how cost-effective these solutions are. Disaster recovery and high availability configurations no longer need to break the bank.
abstract.4: In this session get advanced tips and tools used by the Oracle’s PeopleSoft administrators at Hennepin County and the City of Minneapolis to make everyday administration easier. Learn about the PeopleSoft cloud architecture that allows administrators to be more efficient with deployment and maintenance tasks. Learn how deployment packages, automated configuration management, automated scripting, and more can change how you maintain your infrastructure and what you can deliver to your business.
abstract.5: This session introduces a library that allows Java programs to stream data into databases at high speed using a simple API. The typical use case consists of a large number of clients or IoT devices emitting data to be persisted and that must not be blocked, waiting for a synchronous response from the database. The library relies on advanced performance and scalability techniques such as direct path insertion protocol, partitioning, sharding, and data affinity. The session includes a working prototype (demo) and code samples using the library.
abstract.6: The most important rule with respect to data is to never put yourself into an unrecoverable situation. The importance of this guideline cannot be stressed enough—that's why backup and recovery are the most essential skills you need to be a successful DBA. These are also essential skills if you are seeking any Oracle certification. In this session learn about a free tool called CrashSimulator that simulates close to 50 different disaster scenarios. Test your firefighter skill and ensure that you will be prepared to protect your company’s business continuity and availability. All lessons are applicable for both on-premises and cloud environments.
abstract.7: Your organization is awash with data—much of it likely sitting in spreadsheets and datamarts or warehouses. In this session see some innovative examples of analytics applications you can easily build with Oracle Essbase using templates for HR, projects, and survey analytics. More options are available in the Oracle Analytics Cloud store, and you can easily share your work with others there as well.
abstract.8: For today's fast-changing world with daily releases, its critical to make sure that applications remain secure. Most developers today embed security with application logic, making it difficult to maintain and secure. In this session learn how centralizing data access security in the database and keeping it separate from application logic dramatically improves security and reduces development time. Oracle’s application security solutions, Oracle Label Security and Oracle Virtual Private Database, meet different authorization use cases. Using innovative data security technologies from Oracle, you can now be confident about the security of your cloud applications and still meet your daily deadlines.
abstract.9: Oracle’s research and development leadership is committed to fostering an environment of innovation. Oracle Retail teams stay educated and immersed in the latest trends and emerging technology. Oracle also encourages experimentation through a concept called Science Fair. Come to this session to learn how Oracle delivers a complete digital store solution that enables the integration of store infrastructure and consumer engagement technologies to help your stores gain a competitive advantage.
abstract.10: Bank integration is one of the key project activities in any ERP implementation. From bank connectivity to payment formats, each bank integration aspect has its unique challenges. In this session walk through a hypothetical timeline for the key tasks and deliverables while keeping in mind the constraints of the bank and other parties. Discover the five major US bank documents (check, ACH, epayables, ISO 20022, and BAI2) and see how Oracle Cloud provides a head start for these activities and helps you streamline processes.
abstract.11: In this session learn how to use Oracle's secure enterprise cloud infrastructure to deploy DBaaS and MWaaS with higher performance, agility, and security while lowering costs. This solution enables you to consolidate existing deployments leveraging a unified umbrella of services, with your choice of acquisition model. This technical session includes specific deployment details along with different strategies to deploy DBaaS and MWaaS on your premises, and explores how to prepare for a future move into Oracle Cloud. See a demo of using Oracle technologies to deploy DBaaS and MWaaS, and lift-and-shift databases.
abstract.12: Cloud is the new normal for enterprise workloads. Oracle Cloud Infrastructure is built from the ground up to be an enterprise cloud, equally capable of running traditional multitiered enterprise applications, high-performance workloads, and modern serverless and container-based architectures. Oracle Cloud Infrastructure offers a variety of services including compute, storage, networking, and database, that can help you build secure, scalable, high-performance, and reliable applications while leveraging hybrid resources and lowering your overall TCO. It all starts with good solution architecture. In this session learn architecture patterns and best practices for building, deploying and running enterprise workloads in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.
abstract.13: Setting up highly available architectures for your Oracle applications including Oracle E-Business Suite, JD Edwards, and PeopleSoft used to be difficult and expensive. But moving them to the cloud—specifically Oracle Cloud Infrastructure—allows you to easily and cost-effectively take advantage of platform capabilities. In this session learn how easy it is to set up a high availability configuration distributed across availability domains that are fault tolerant against any imaginable catastrophe and replicated across geographic regions. Take advantage of services such as DNS and Ravello to modernize your app infrastructure and utilize hybrid connectivity solutions to maintain on-premises integrations.
abstract.14: In this session learn the best practices for creating and managing instances and their associated resources in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute Classic and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure.
abstract.15: You chose Oracle Database to help your organization deliver superior business results. Now learn how to further enhance the availability, scalability, and performance of all Oracle Database installations (Oracle RAC, single instance, and even in the cloud) by staying on top of the latest success factors and best practices developed by Oracle experts. In this session Oracle experts discuss proven best practices to provide better support through targeted diagnostics, work more efficiently, upgrade more easily, and avoid unforeseen incidents. Topics include how to keep Oracle Databases in check, monitor crucial aspects of your environment, and simplify diagnostic collection.
abstract.16: In this session learn how certain choices can impact performance and stability of a DBaaS instance. If a database deployment on Oracle Database Cloud Service is performing poorly or is running out of storage, you can scale up the environment supporting the database deployment. Occasionally, the need to scale arises from some change made to the database or backup configuration after it was created. For example, if the decision to use Oracle Database In-Memory was made after database creation, you might need to scale up the compute shape to one of the high-memory options, such as scaling from OC4 - 2 OCPU, 15 GB RAM to OC2M - 2 OCPU, 30 GB RAM. Learn the dos and don’ts for DBaaS instance administration.
abstract.17: In this session hear Oracle Support experts share best practices that can help you maximize your Oracle’s PeopleSoft applications and support experience. Topics include PeopleSoft Fluid User Interface, classic plus user interface, automation, and moving to Oracle Cloud.
abstract.18: In this session learn about the best practices for configuring and troubleshooting issues in the security service layer. Data security is provided for data in transit and data at rest. Security of data in transit is achieved through network encryption. Data at rest is kept secure through encryption of data stored in database data files and backups. Data in Oracle Database files, including backups, is secured by encryption implemented through a key management framework. Security of data across the network is provided by native Oracle Net Services encryption and integrity capabilities.
abstract.19: Interested in finding free tools/services to proactively avoid business problems and optimize your use of Oracle products and cloud services? This session provides users and administrators insight on how to identify the Oracle Support proactive tools and services best suited to their needs and how to best leverage these tools and services. Gain insight and take away practical advice you can apply to your business and operational needs.
abstract.20: Many companies have legacy systems that successfully get the job done every day but don’t conform to corporate server refresh standards. There are many reasons for this scenario. In this session explore these reasons and see if there are unique handling considerations or things that can be done to mitigate problems. Are there reasons to upgrade? Sure. Are there reasons to stay where you are? Sure.  Hear a discussion about rationales for both, and strategies to manage things along the way.
abstract.21: Still trying to make sense of Oracle's new database release model? Wondering how best to pace your upgrade and patching cycles? Come to this session to get insider recommendations on best upgrade and patching strategies. Get tips on testing and ways to minimize or even eliminate downtime from the team that produces the patches for on-premises releases and Oracle Database Cloud Service.
abstract.22: Microservices are the de facto standard for any new application being developed. With their decentralized nature they enable scalability, autonomy, and flexibility in modern applications. But it always gets tricky when it comes to the data. "Code is easy, state is hard" is the motto often heard. Naturally, a lot of microservices architectures do not address the data aspect, leaving it up to you to figure it out. In this session learn how to apply data management to a microservices architecture. Discover where the synergies between the two lie and how to avoid common pitfalls so you can apply the best of both worlds in your next application design.
abstract.23: This session explores the Oracle Cloud full solution architecture, highlighting security features for Oracle Exadata Cloud and how to use them to protect data in public, private, and hybrid clouds. Topics include secure shell (ssh) access, network firewalls and software-defined networks, Oracle Database Vault, Oracle Database Firewall and Audit Vault, transparent data encryption, and ssh key management. Learn about the security controls that separate Oracle Cloud operations and customer data access. Get a comprehensive, end-to-end understanding of Oracle’s security products and how they work together to provide unique and effective solutions to modern security challenges.
abstract.24: In this session learn about DBaas backup in detail, including the options available and how customers can change their configuration as per their need. Topics include common mistakes/errors related to the cloud backup and their solutions, best practices for DBaaS backup, and how to check and manage backups in the container.
abstract.25: This must-see session explores the technical details of Oracle’s breakthrough in revolutionary Software in Silicon technologies, so you can fully take advantage of these new features. Learn from Oracle engineers how to use this technology to enhance security, efficiency, and performance for Oracle Database and other software, in your own data center or in the cloud. Learn how Oracle’s research and development focuses simultaneously in hardware and software to deliver unmatched results in real-world implementations.
abstract.26: Are you looking for a way to consolidate your databases and applications onto fewer systems and still be able to isolate the workloads and save money on software licensing?  Virtualization provides a solution to utilize resources efficiently to run different workloads and easily move VMs to another on-premises system or even the cloud. Kernel-based virtual machine (KVM), one of the most popular hypervisors, is supported on Oracle Database Appliance to run your database and applications on a single platform.  Attend this session to learn how to deploy KVM to provision and manage your databases and applications while controlling your software licensing costs on Oracle Database Appliance and the cloud.
abstract.27: This session focuses on a modern DevOps approach based on the concept of containerization. Learn how to build a Docker container running an Oracle Application Development Framework application. Hear how to create and push an image to a repository. Get familiar with building continuous integration and deployment pipeline by the means of Docker containers and Kubernetes cluster in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure. The session highlights best practices for development, deployment, testing, and orchestration tasks in the containerized environment.
abstract.28: If you are planning to implement a microservices architecture with the flexibility to support multiple technology stacks for faster and quality development, you are moving in the direction of implementing a polyglot pattern. To manage this polyglot landscape you need an efficient DevOps platform. Join this session to learn how to use the DevOps recipe for multistack microservices. Learn how to develop, build, and deploy your polyglot code using Oracle Developer Cloud Service. See how you can use Oracle Developer Cloud Service to automate the continuous integration and continuous deployment pipeline for a polyglot microservice architecture and learn how flexibility meets consistency on Oracle Cloud.
abstract.29: With data and analytics driving digital transformation, organizations in every industry are looking to data technologies to enable transformation through specific use cases. In this session see how different combinations of Oracle’s cloud services centered around a data lake can address many different use cases.
abstract.30: GitHub is a community where more than 27 million people learn, share, and work together to build software. In this session Oracle experts share Oracle's contributions to the open source community. Learn about the interesting projects hosted on GitHub such as Vagrant Boxes for VirtualBox, a Terraform provider for Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, GraalVM, Oracle Docker images, and Kubernetes. See how to automate your DevOps tasks easily in the cloud or on-premises.
abstract.31: A quick diversion from our now traditional featured short talks, this year our EMEA ACE Directors will share their biggest errors and what they learned from it. A fast, fun session that will energize you on your Oracle OpenWorld 2018 experience.
abstract.32: Oracle aims to deliver differentiated value to customers through a personalized support experience. Oracle's Service Request Transactional Survey is important for global systems support to continuously monitor and assess levels of customer satisfaction among Oracle's customer community. Customers initiate dialogue, lend insights, actively partner with the company, and participate in continuous improvement and feedback efforts. They tell others about their experiences and the business value of Oracle Support.  In this session learn how global systems support incorporates feedback and suggestions into business planning so that Oracle may better meet your needs.
abstract.33: Oracle Database 12c Release 2 and Oracle Database 18c are packed with enhancements for DBAs and developers. In this session learn about all the pertinent new features that will change how you perform maintenance and tune the database. Be prepared to have mind overloaded. Topics covered include upgrading to Oracle Database 12.2, online improvements, the partitioning option, the multitenancy (pluggable database) option, Oracle Data Guard, Oracle Recovery Manager, Oracle Real Application Clusters, Oracle Automatic Storage Management Cluster File System, in-memory features, and database upgrade options. Oracle DBAs/developers can take immediate advantage of these new features.
abstract.34: This Oracle Development session summarizes practical tips and lessons learned from performance-tuning and benchmarking the world’s largest Oracle E-Business Suite environments. Get concrete tips and techniques for identifying and resolving performance bottlenecks on all layers of the technology stack, and learn how Oracle’s engineered systems such as Oracle Exadata and Oracle Exalogic can dramatically improve the performance.
abstract.35: Blockchain is hot, and if you have qualified use cases, this session can help you get started implementing them. Learn how to determine when Blockchain is the right approach to distributed enterprise applications, architect Blockchain network topology, implement smart-contracts, and build/integrate client applications to create your first Blockchain network. Specific examples are used to illustrate the process and show step-by-step evolution of a Blockchain application.
abstract.36: PeopleSoft is the most flexible ERP solution in the world. But today, with user demands for a modern user experience, selective adoption, and continuous delivery, it is more important than ever to avoid customizations. In this session learn tips and tricks to change the behavior and appearance of your PeopleSoft applications without modifying delivered code.
abstract.37: The session demonstrates the testing of Oracle Database (either application tests or Oracle Database tests) inside a Docker environment. Based on a real-world example of using Oracle/Docker in a test environment, this session is for anyone interested in gaining a better understanding of the advantages and disadvantages of running Oracle in a Docker environment. The session includes a brief overview of Docker, reasons why to run Oracle in Docker, a demo of running an application test (using Oracle Database) in Docker environment, and a demo of running Oracle Database in a Docker container in Oracle Cloud.
abstract.38: Ever wondered how to format Oracle standard reports to meet your requirements? With Oracle ERP it’s simple, and this session shows you how. Learn how to use Oracle Business Intelligence Publisher to extend the output of standard reports to flat Excel templates, so you can do Excel-based analysis on ERP data. Learn how to make your format the default output format or output both standard and the extended format. See a demo using the subledger account analysis report and the fixed-asset reserve ledger report as use cases and discover how to format the output. This capability improves productivity and empowers the end user to focus on analyzing the data instead of formatting it.
abstract.39: This session explores how to start with Terraform in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure to define your ideal data center. See how to use Oracle REST Data Services with Exadata for next-generation application development on Oracle Exadata Cloud to gain unprecedented data processing speed and agility for data science work. Along the way learn the technical details of Exadata’s secret sauce and how to use it with your applications.
abstract.40: Even in the Oracle Cloud, rare and random short-lived performance incidents can occur. These incidents present Oracle Cloud DBAs with a challenge. In this session learn why active session history (ASH) is so powerful, how it works, and how to use ASH to solve complex performance incidents. Using only four free scripts, walk through an incident analysis process. Plus see how to visualize the performance situation using the free statistics package R.
abstract.41: A strategy of securing all the data in your cloud is attainable today through Oracle technology. In this technical session get engineering insight on how you can easily build an end-to-end encrypted infrastructure throughout web tier, Java app tier, and database tier, all with near-zero performance impact. Best practices for protecting customer and application data while in motion through your cloud, or at rest in disk, are also covered.
abstract.42: In this session learn about the latest Oracle’s JD Edwards cloud offerings including valuable tips and tricks for success based on real customer experiences. JD Edwards support covers key topics such as Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, one-click provisioning, and migration to the cloud.
abstract.43: Historically, companies have not had controls in place to ensure their business-critical systems do not fall out of compliance and result in potentially steep fines. Oracle E-Business Suite running on the cloud can help companies implement advanced controls to stay in compliance with regulations such as GDPR and SoX. In this session learn about the audit and compliance advantages of running Oracle E-Business Suite in the cloud versus on premises. Controls such as user and responsibility level, environment configuration, network information, password policy, and patch management among others are part of the audit and compliance baseline included.
abstract.44: MySQL’s NDB cluster is a partitioned distributed engine completely built around a virtual machine and based on an asynchronous event-driven programming model. Using this approach NDB executes single MySQL queries in parallel, and scales linearly over many nodes and to highest levels of performance. In this session learn about the advantages, disadvantages, and sometimes surprising compromises of this architecture.
abstract.45: Ensuring that visitors can quickly locate the products they want is key to any successful buying experience. In this session learn how to personalize the commerce site experience in microseconds by enriching search results with consumer interests based on data-driven intelligence. Learn how to leverage AI to intelligently connect experiences across commerce, marketing, sales, and service to increase customer acquisition rates and drive sales. Get an understanding of how to manage the new human/machine partnership in modern applications.
abstract.46: Are you getting most out of your investments in Oracle Cloud Infrastructure? In this session learn how to optimize your Oracle Database performance after cloud migration. Learn about dynamic CPU/storage scaling and how to build petabyte-scale storage in a matter of minutes and grow your capacity on-demand without predicting the future. Learn about best practices for managing Oracle Database on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, including backup/restore, performance tuning, schema design, and day-to-day administration using Oracle Database CLI and/or Oracle Enterprise Monitor tools. Learn how to build a zero data loss solution on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure by taking advantage of modern infrastructure, build disaster recovery on Exadata, and optimize backup costs.
abstract.47: In this session learn how to tune your Oracle Linux systems to maximize performance on bare metal and in the cloud. Configure Oracle Linux, VMs, and containers to provide resilient services and mission-critical workloads. This session presents troubleshooting and tracing tools to help you get your systems running with maximum performance. Learn how Oracle's contributions to the open source Linux community improve your enterprise deployments. Attend this session to discover the tools you need to keep your data center operating at maximum efficiency.
abstract.48: Modern web applications are based on hundreds or even thousands microservices running in containers orchestrated by Kubernetes. Stateful microservices must persist data. There are several models for data consistency with microservices. This session examines the deployment models of microservices and databases, and then discusses various persistence models including direct connectivity (e.g., JDBC, Node.js), delegation to a proxy server or an event-based persistence provider, and the most challenging model: a highly consistent persistence where changes by multiple microservices contribute to a business transaction. The session explores the various approaches to high consistency, the SAGA pattern, and promises, and includes live demos.
abstract.49: Have you customized Oracle E-Business Suite? Attend this Oracle Development session to learn about selecting the best upgrade approach for existing customizations. Learn about the new customization standards required by the Edition-Based Redefinition feature of Oracle Database to be compliant with the Online Patching feature of Oracle E-Business Suite. Hear about customization use cases, tools, and technologies you can use to ensure that all your customizations are preserved during and after the upgrade.
abstract.50: The dramatic efficiencies of deploying databases in cloud configurations are worthless if they come at the expense of isolation. Attend this session to learn about the technologies that deliver the isolation behind Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud.
abstract.51: Enterprise-scale database cloud services demand sophisticated management frameworks to support the entire database lifecycle. In this session learn from the architects of Oracle Autonomous Data Warehouse Cloud how to deploy this technology to manage your private database cloud.
abstract.52: The role of the DBA changes with the cloud and autonomous managed services. The multitenant architecture is the foundation for these new roles. The container database/pluggable database (CDB/PDB) paradigm enforces role segregation between the container DBA and the application. In a DevOps environment, you need the finer access privilege definition that comes in Oracle Database 12.1 (common/local users) and Oracle Database 12.2 (lockdown profiles, PDB isolation), and that was improved in Oracle Database 18c. In this session learn to administer a cloud or on-premises database and give PDB administration rights to application teams. See how to grant database access to a developer on a PDB with Oracle Database 18c. Discover the new features, see a demo, and learn best practices.
abstract.53: MySQL InnoDB cluster provides a high-level, easy-to-use solution for MySQL high availability. Combining MySQL group replication with MySQL router and the MySQL shell into an integrated solution, InnoDB cluster provides easy setup and management of MySQL instances into a fault-tolerant database service. In this session learn the steps to set up a basic InnoDB cluster, integrate it with applications, and recognize and react to common failure scenarios that would otherwise lead to a database outage.
abstract.54: Powering the world with JavaScript?  It's all about data management and scalability. In this session learn the best ways of using Node.js to get data into and out of Oracle Database. This session showcases the node-oracledb module for building great applications. Learn how to make asynchronous applications scale and perform. Keep up-to-date with all the latest on this rapidly changing environment.
abstract.55: Scheduling maintenance operations can be the biggest bane a DBA faces. How do you get the job done without upsetting virtually all your users?  Continuous system operations is a key success criterion for any cloud environment and for many on-premises setups.  Come to this session to learn from Oracle Development how to conduct operations with zero or minimal impact.  Dive into the details of implementing the new and improved toolsets available with Oracle Database 18c, and how they can provide answers to this pervasive problem.
abstract.56: Database operations account for the larger part of applications performance and scalability. Java applications that use an RDBMS must follow known best practices, consider database proxies, and embrace asynchronous database access using reactive and functional programming. This session revisits the known best practices for speeding up database connectivity, speeding up SQL statements processing, optimizing network traffic, and in-place processing. The session also covers scaling out Java applications workload using sharded databases, multitenant databases, database proxy, and the upcoming asynchronous Java database access API. This new API proposal is an entirely separate API that provides completely nonblocking access to databases.
abstract.57: Oracle Adaptive Intelligent Apps leverage machine learning and artificial intelligence to deliver significant results for retailers. In this session explore the role of artificial intelligence, machine learning, and decision science across the Oracle Retail portfolio. Oracle is proud to partner with universities including MIT, Stanford, and the University of South Carolina to explore how these technologies enhance next-generation solutions, such as how the ability to identify influential customers using social media and transaction data can help retailers lift revenue.
abstract.58: Oracle Advanced Collections has come a long way in providing rich features for collection agents to view and act on critical tasks and reduce days sales outstanding. In this session see a demo of new functionality including a dispute process that creates an automated credit memo based on approval thresholds and AR help desk routing. Learn about the Collections Workbench for tracking, monitoring, and responding to delinquent receivables. The session also explores the notes and aging and communication feature. Get tips and tricks as well as lessons learned implementing Oracle Advanced Collections.
abstract.59: In this session see real cases of moving Oracle Business Intelligence Enterprise Edition on-premises to Oracle Analytics Cloud. See the steps to perform this migration and explore the issues that can come up and how to troubleshoot them. In addition explore the most common administration tasks. This session also includes live Oracle Analytics Cloud demos.
abstract.60: Oracle Database 18c is now available, and it builds on Oracle Database 12cR2. Both solutions offer a broad range of features for the developer, from a small addition like RESTful calls to the database to large-scale enablement using Oracle Multitenant. This session explores how developers and DBAs can work together to start using 10 of the top new features that make it easier to get the job done. If you are a developer or DBA, this session is for you.
abstract.61: Oracle Database Appliance provides the lowest entry cost of all Oracle’s engineered systems.  It is architected with Oracle Database best practices built in and takes less than two hours to deploy a 2-node Oracle RAC cluster—the complete storage and software stack.  How can Oracle Database Appliance accomplish this? Attend this session to gain a deeper insight into the design and discover how it can reduce your risk to implement highly available databases environments so you can focus on the business instead of chasing down patches and storage topologies.
abstract.62: Some might think Docker is for developers only, but this is not really the case. Docker is here to stay and there will be more and more of it in the future. In this session learn what Docker is and how it works, then run a few examples of how to create a database environment within just a few minutes—perfect for testing, development, and possibly even production systems.
abstract.63: Although Oracle Data Integrator is a well-known ELT tool for heterogenous platforms, it also can be used to load data from or to Oracle Database in the cloud and other cloud vendors. In this session hear the ways to integrate Oracle Data Integrator with not only Oracle cloud services, but also the other cloud vendors as well. Discover how you can benefit from Oracle Data Integrator with SaaS, PaaS, IaaS, and DaaS solutions, as well as Oracle Database Cloud Service, Oracle Business Intelligence Cloud Service, Oracle GoldenGate Cloud Service, and Oracle Data Integration Platform Cloud.
abstract.64: Join this Oracle Development session to understand the new architecture introduced with the inclusion of Oracle Fusion Middleware and Oracle WebLogic Server in the application tier technology stack for Oracle E-Business Suite 12.2. Learn about Oracle Fusion Middleware configuration, administration, upgrade, and patching. Details regarding the Oracle WebLogic Server domain and managed servers architecture and adding and deleting nodes and managed servers are covered. Log file location and basic monitoring and troubleshooting tips are also discussed.
abstract.65: Wouldn't it be great if you had a simple report that could tell you if you had any critical issues in your Oracle E-Business Suite environment, and it also gave you simple directions for fixing them? That amazing report does exist, and it is generated from the analyzer diagnostics. These are the most important support tools available today. If you integrate analyzers into your best practices and maintenance, you can avoid many critical and time-sensitive issues that are costly to your business.  In this session see how to utilize these FREE tools and get started today.
abstract.66: In this session learn about Oracle E-Business Suite automation in Oracle Cloud and the role of support for the application, automation, maintenance, and infrastructure.
abstract.67: You can run Oracle E-Business Suite on the Oracle Cloud Platform, and options for doing so continue to expand. In this session an esteemed panel of Oracle E-Business Suite customers and partners share their experiences adopting Oracle Cloud Infrastructure services including Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute Classic and Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute, and associated platform services (PaaS).  Hear about drivers that led them to choose Oracle Cloud Infrastructure and learn about their cloud topologies, deployment methods, and lessons learned. The session includes a Q&A period in which the panel fields questions from the audience.
abstract.68: In this session Oracle Development takes a deep dive into the latest and greatest Exadata high availability capabilities and best practices.  Attendees gain deep knowledge of Oracle Maximum Availability Architecture guidelines that will enable them to achieve the highest level of availability with their Exadata systems, whether they are housed on-premises or in the cloud. Topics discussed in this session are applicable to any workload, such as OLTP, data warehousing, consolidation, and high performance in-memory processing. If you care about high availability, this session is for you.
abstract.69: In this session learn from Oracle development about the best practices to implement Active-Active replication using Oracle GoldenGate. Learn the various conflict resolution methods, how to reduce the number of conflicts that can occur, and how to easily automate conflict detection and resolution using the new automatic CDR feature in Oracle Database.
abstract.70: In this session learn best practices for implementing Oracle GoldenGate using the microservices architecture. The session includes different use cases for the Oracle GoldenGate microservices architecture for mass deployment and simplified management of the overall replication environment.
abstract.71: In this session learn how Oracle JavaScript Extension Toolkit composite components enable a higher level of productivity, agility, and maintainability of rich client web applications. The reusable components can be shared across pages, applications, and teams—and even across the global community. The components can be developed separately from the applications that consume them and can be deployed and updated independently. They are also well-suited to be used as the user interface for a microservice that is mashed up in a larger web application or portal. Learn the why and how of Oracle JavaScript Extension Toolkit composite components, tooling to use for productivity and agility, and a proven approach for microservice UI implementation.
abstract.72: Join Oracle development for the latest updates on high availability best practices in this well-established and heavily attended technical deep-dive session. Learn how to optimize all aspects of Oracle Data Guard 18c. See how to use session draining, application continuity, Oracle Database In-Memory with Oracle RAC, and Oracle GoldenGate with Oracle Data Guard to mask outages and planned maintenance from users and to accelerate time to repair. Hear about the latest high availability best practices with Oracle Multitenant and understand how the new sharded architecture for OLTP applications can achieve even higher levels of high availability and fault isolation. Find out how everything you know about Oracle Maximum Availability Architecture on-premises can be deployed in the cloud.
abstract.73: In this entertaining and lively joint session with the Oracle MiniCluster lead architect learn about Oracle's best practices for implementing and running Oracle MiniCluster for maximum availability, serviceability, and operational simplicity. The session also includes examples of what happens when those best practices aren't followed.
abstract.74: This session presents best practices for installing, provisioning, and ongoing operation of the Oracle Private Cloud Appliance. Learn detailed best practices in the areas of systems monitoring, networking, storage, virtual machine architecture, and layout. Also learn about integration with other Oracle products such as the Oracle ZFS Storage Appliance, Oracle Enterprise Manager, and the use of Oracle Linux as a utility VM.
abstract.75: The definition of a data lake is broad, and although everyone has their own interpretation, Oracle’s data platform enforces one meaning. Oracle’s data lake is next-generation, built on an object store, and utilizes a centralized data catalog and elastic compute. Oracle’s data platform enforces this definition and ensures all data within the data lake is fully secured and governed, including data at rest and in motion. Join this session led by Oracle product management to see how Oracle’s data platform can jumpstart your data lake project as well as load, manage, secure, and govern it end-to-end. Get a deep dive focused on big data and data lake functionality and see a live demo of an end-to-end data lake use case.
abstract.76: In this session hear from Oracle SOA Suite product management, product development experts, and customers who have mastered the art of developing a service-oriented architecture using Oracle SOA Suite, and have extended that to the cloud with a hybrid integration platform approach using Oracle Integration Cloud. Get tips for how to extend your current Oracle SOA Suite investments with Oracle Integration Cloud through migration, extending to SaaS, and reusing existing SOA services on-premises from new cloud channels.
abstract.77: In this session learn how to optimize your development experience, as well as achieve more performant and secure code. See via live demo how to make the most of your time with Oracle SQL Developer. This session is meant to be an interactive experience, so bring your questions and current challenges.
abstract.78: How do cloud services impact the way you approach your infrastructure investment and strategy for success? How do retail teams need to work and think differently? In this session hear an interactive conversation focused on preparing for and supporting a cloud deployment.
abstract.79: In this session learn best practice tips from the development group responsible for Oracle Database client APIs.  Learn about the relationship between the application and database, and see how to create efficient and resilient systems. Get application-centric answers to the top questions about program interaction with SQL and PL/SQL, on effectively using Oracle data types, and how to work with large data sets. Examples are applicable to cloud and on-premise applications using C, Python, Node.js, ODP.Net, Java, PHP, and other scripting languages.
abstract.80: In this session learn about the activities that should be performed for a successful upgrade to Oracle Database 18c while maintaining the same or better performance. Hear about the recommend tools to collect diagnostic data, tune SQL statements, and fix any database tuning problem encountered after upgrading the database.
abstract.81: The session covers lessons learned, tips/tricks, recommendations, best practices, gotchas, and a whole lot more on how to effectively use Oracle Enterprise Manager Cloud Control for quick, easy, and intuitive performance tuning of your Oracle Database 18c. Come learn from the experts how to effectively employ Oracle Enterprise Manager for tuning, troubleshooting, and monitoring your Oracle Database cloud ecosystem.
abstract.82: Automation impacts many aspects of life, from banking to transportation and customer service.  It offers benefits in repeatable, simple, even dangerous situations, and where accuracy is required. Automation is gradually being embraced and depended upon. However, humans are still better at several aspects of interaction.  Particularly empathy, but also complex, new, and unique situations. Oracle believes its customers receive the best experience from the harmony and partnership that both humans and automation provides, especially in customer support. In this session walk through an Oracle Service experience to understand the benefit to you of the perfect partnership of humans and automation.
abstract.83: Python is hot and desirable. The cx_Oracle API for Oracle Database adds spice that hotness. In this session see how cx_Oracle can be used to build functional, high-performance Python apps that make the best use of database functionality and resources. The cx_Oracle interface is arguably the most popular way of accessing Oracle Database. This session shows how to use its features in the best possible way.
abstract.84: In this session learn some of the tips and techniques of successfully managing a database infrastructure in the real world from someone who has been a DBA for 22 years and counting. Each recommendation is explained with justification. Some examples include installing patches in a different Oracle home, enabling simple auditing, using Oracle Recovery Manager to validate and restore previews, using pfile instead of spfile, and many others. This is an update of a previously delivered very popular Oracle OpenWorld session.
abstract.85: Recent Oracle Database releases include significant new features that streamline user administration, reduce database attack surfaces, and protect personally identifiable information, and other sensitive data. In this session learn about the new way to authenticate and authorize database users in Active Directory. Explore review recent security innovations including privilege analysis, database vault simulation mode, data redaction, online encryption, and passwordless schemas. See how to assess the security of your database with Oracle Database Security Assessment Tool. Attend this session and you'll be able take advantage of these features next week to create a more secure database environment.
abstract.86: In this session learn about the best practices to deploy Java applications on Oracle WebLogic Server and maximize performance while achieving enterprise-grade security and reliability. Get firsthand technical advice from Oracle experts on how to use the latest Oracle products to build first-class Java applications. Witness a live demo of Oracle WebLogic Server running on Oracle SPARC technology and understand why this combination creates unique advantages for running Java middleware.
abstract.87: Bringing Oracle Databases to the cloud involves major changes, including hardware resources that are no longer static and a pay-per-use expense model. It used to be that as long as servers were surviving the workload, no one cared whether they were underutilized. Now unused resources can be immediately monetized, so the total quality of the code base (and performance tuning) has a direct impact on cost. This session examines some of the corresponding best practices including code instrumentation, profiling, code management, and resource optimization. Learn to make your system cloud-friendly.
abstract.88: SmartDB lets just two teams build an OLTP application. One team exposes the database as a hard-shell PL/SQL API defined as JSON in/JSON out functions. The other program is a modern browser-based UI in JavaScript. Oracle REST Data Services acts as the semantics-free (and therefore maintenance-free) protocol adapter between Oracle Net Services and REST. The carefully designed API contract brings minimum coupling between modules, letting the two teams work independently. In particular, each can fix its bugs without talking to the other. This session shows you how to use edition-based redefinition to fix bugs in the hard-shell implementation with zero downtime, and flip end-user sessions to the patched version from inside the database. Only SmartDB can implement the flip for every server call.
abstract.89: This Oracle Development session is ideal for organizations thinking about upgrading to Oracle E-Business Suite 12.2. It covers the fundamentals of upgrading, including the technology stack components and supported upgrade paths. Hear from Oracle Development about the recommended practices for executing the technical upgrade, with special considerations for minimizing your downtime. Also get to know about relatively recent upgrade resources.
abstract.90: You just got the keys to the world’s most powerful cloud: Oracle Cloud. What is the first thing you should do with it? Don’t panic! Thousands of organizations have already figured it out and this session presents the most interesting ones. The objective is to send you away with basic tips on customer-validated use cases for Oracle Management Cloud that, as a DBA, you should know about and be able to implement within a matter of hours. Spoiler alert: This session may not be able to cover all 99, but it does provide a catalog of all of them.
abstract.91: The advent of the cloud and the introduction of Oracle Autonomous Database Cloud presents opportunities for every organization, but what's the future role for the DBA? In this session explore how the role of the DBA will continue to evolve, and get advice on key skills required to be a successful DBA in the world of the cloud.
abstract.92: In January 2018, the disclosure of three vulnerabilities caused a public panic. Meltdown (CVE-2017-5754) and Spectre (CVE-2017-5715 and CVE-2017-5753) resulted from flaws in modern processors, and had significant impacts across a wide swathe of on-premises and cloud services, affecting both commercial and open source software and hardware.  In this panel discussion security experts on the front line review how these vulnerabilities came about, the technical responses necessary to mitigate these issues, Oracle's internal actions in response to these new threats, the lingering impact of them, and the sometimes-incorrect assumptions made when responding to these vulnerabilities.
abstract.93: The skill set of a database practitioner is much more than what is read in the documentation, on blogs, or on StackOverflow. It is the knowledge from years of trial and error, experimentation, and sometimes painful failures. The problem is it takes time—a long, long time—to build that experience. This session aims to fast-track that path. Get a collection of hints, tips, features, and techniques picked up from the smartest people in the community.
abstract.94: What if you could take the hassle out of connecting SaaS and on-premises systems with prebuilt adapters and machine learning–powered data mapping recommendations? In this session learn how advances in integration and Robotic Process Automation (RPA) technology are transforming IT for speed to revenue and digital business agility. Explore how AI is changing everything - including integration. See what the future of integration looks like now and hear how Tupperware is tackling legacy complexity API-first.
abstract.95: Getting information in and out of any system can be challenging, especially to clients that are new to Oracle Cloud. This session provides information for sending integration into and out of Oracle Transportation Management Cloud Service. Topics included are integration in WMServlet, WebServices, and external systems, as well as common troubleshooting tips.
abstract.96: Oracle enterprise platforms provide a wealth of tools to monitor and analyze infrastructure utilization, and to identify bottlenecks or misconfigurations. Analyzing performance of key cloud applications, including Java-based and database workloads, is key to utilizing your cloud infrastructure efficiently. In this technical session explore measures accessible through Oracle Solaris commands, with special focus on the latest SPARC M8 processor, Software in Silicon acceleration, and memory utilization analysis. The session also includes a deep dive into some aspects of the processor pipeline and explains how to benefit from low-level event monitoring.
abstract.97: The session explores the plusses and minuses of the new self-driving Oracle Autonomous Database Cloud. Learn what you need to know to migrate, manage, and assess this new database and see where it fits and where it doesn't fit.  The session also explores the things you must consider and do before you move this database and gives a peek into the future and how to merge into the fast lane.
abstract.98: Many DBAs and architects think they understand Oracle Database replication. But it is often physical replication only, performed by Oracle Data Guard, rather than logical replication as done by Oracle GoldenGate, Oracle Streams, and others. There are three fundamental principles that govern how these logical replication tools operate, centered on conversion, identification, and conflict handling of the replicated data. This session outlines these principles and how they function, and provides demos as well. Other topics addressed include managing conflicts, commit strategies, updating PKs, and the difference between logical and physical replication. This information is good grounding for Oracle Database data, whether on-premises or moving to/in the cloud.
abstract.99: Enterprise deployments of Oracle software products nearly always consist of a collection of different software products, and some of them might even be open source software packages. When connecting to Oracle Database, Java middleware, or other applications, you often need to build a software package on your platform. In this session get deep technical guidance on how to generate better-performing open source binaries for the Oracle Solaris operating system, especially when building these packages on a SPARC-based platform.
abstract.100: Are you getting the most out of Oracle Order Management? Oracle has invested many years of engineering in its core Oracle Order Management products to deliver a huge set of capabilities we know are often overlooked. Customers sometimes wonder whether there might be a better way to execute a business process within Oracle Order Management. In this session Oracle Order Management team members share insights and experiences from watching thousands of customers go live. Get practical tips and tricks for using product features to manage order fulfillment operations more efficiently. Topics include standard features worth turning on, features often skipped, other tips and recommendations that enable customers to get the most out of their investment.
abstract.101: The CIO mandate is cloud strategy. As a DBA, you have to choose the best cloud platform for your Oracle Databases. For years, you have been running these databases in your on-premises environment in a reliable, secure, highly available and performant manner. But what happens to these metrics in the cloud? Can you meet your SLAs? Does it make your life easier? Does it satisfy the CIO mandate? Come to this session to learn the tips and trips of deploying Oracle Databases in the cloud to make your deployment a success from the start. This session examines how to avoid the common pitfalls. It also looks at techniques that you can leverage to simplify and enhance your experience and improve the productivity of your team and your end users.
abstract.102: In the face of increasing hacking threats, Oracle Linux and Oracle VM provide features that can help keep your systems secure and improve the speed and stability of your operations. In this session learn about Ksplice's zero-downtime security patching for your operating system and hypervisors, security best practices, and secure remote access on-premises or in the cloud with Oracle Secure Global Desktop.
abstract.103: Advanced compression is a key technology for improving performance and reducing the storage footprint of your database. In this session learn the top 10 insights (maybe more) about Oracle compression including best practices, tips and tricks, how other organizations use compression, and compression insights that you need to know. The areas covered include data compression (advanced row and hybrid columnar), index compression (advanced index and prefix), LOB compression (SecureFiles LOB), automating compression (automatic data optimization), and backup compression (Oracle Recovery Manager).
abstract.104: Oracle's Siebel CRM is at the center of your business. In this session learn directly from Oracle Support  what Siebel in the cloud offers, including tips and tricks for maintaining and upgrading your CRM application to the latest Siebel release.
abstract.105: User-defined attributes framework provides the ability to capture information across various Oracle E-Business Suite modules. It is particularly useful if users have exhausted the limit of predefined attributes in the existing descriptive flexfields. Users can define an unlimited number of attributes and attribute groups, and they can be combined into pages. There are numerous data types and display styles for an attribute and users can select a value from a predefined list of values. These attributes can be populated using interface and APIs as well. This session provides a use case of Oracle Order Management business requirements, solution overview, key features, and a setup of additional attributes.
abstract.106: Today’s businesses must contend with explosive data growth, a struggling global economy, and highly competitive marketplaces. In this session learn how Oracle ZFS Storage Appliance offers leading performance, high scalability, easy manageability, and solid data protection in a general purpose and multiprotocol storage system that is architected to handle the dynamic and high IO loads of cloud environments and virtualization. Hear from experts about the enhanced features of OS 8.7.x, data protection and cloud on-premises-to-cloud gateway, getting the best database performance with hybrid columnar compression and intelligent storage protocol, all-flash storage pool, customization of pool profile for best performance, and the advantages of real-time monitoring with advanced analytics.
abstract.107: Once an enterprise starts using Oracle Application Express, many applications are rapidly created to help manage the business. DBAs start asking questions about managing Oracle Application Express and installing it in Oracle Databases, such as: How can I properly backup and recover Oracle Application Express applications? How do I integrate an Oracle Application Express installation with Oracle E-Business Suite? What are the different component required and supported for the middle tier? Those questions and much more are answered in this session.
abstract.108: Zero Data Loss Recovery Appliance is an industry-innovating, cloud-scale database protection system deployed at hundreds of customers around the world. Its benefits are unparalleled when compared to other backup solutions in the market today, offering the elimination of data loss and backup window, database recoverability validation, and real-time monitoring of enterprisewide data protection status.  In this session get an insider’s look at the system architecture. Hear the latest practices for management, monitoring, high availability, and disaster recovery. Learn tips and tricks for backing up to and restoring from the appliance. Implement these practices at your organization to fulfill database-critical service level agreements.

72.bio:
Senior Director, MAA Best Practices, Server Technologies 
I manage the Exadata, MAA, Zero Data Loss Recovery Appliance (ZDLRA) and Cloud MAA best practices team. The team focuses on building and providing MAA best practices to help prevent, detect, tolerate and repair from all outages and provide a highly available, reliable and scalable solutions for all platforms. Since most of our projects are done on Exadata and  Exadata Cloud, MAA best practices on Exadata and Exadata Cloud tend to be more optimized and integrated than any other platform. We work closely with different development teams to enhance Oracle's overall Exadata, ZDLRA and MAA solutions. We also consult with strategic external and internal customers on HA architectures, features and solutions; however the MAA OTN website is our single external customer portal that contains our MAA documentation, customer case studies and best practices papers. Please refer to MAA OTN website: http://www.oracle.com/goto/maa

The MAA solutions showcase a tight integration of our HA features, providing zero to minimal downtime for planned and unplanned outages while maximizing the ROI and Quality of Service for customers. Some of our projects involve hot patching and rolling upgrades with Oracle clusterware, ASM, Real Application Cluster, Active Data Guard and GoldenGate. We also provide solutions showcasing the fastest repair using Exadata, ASM, RAC, Active Data Guard, RMAN, GoldenGate and Flashback Technologies for example.

* Generic MAA Architecture for DBaaS and all databases (Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum blueprints), HA configuration and operational practices
* Exadata and Exadata Cloud Best Practices

* Cloud MAA best practices including architecture, configuration and life cycle operational practices

101.bio:
Senior Director, MAA Best Practices, Server Technologies 
I manage the Exadata, MAA, Zero Data Loss Recovery Appliance (ZDLRA) and Cloud MAA best practices team. The team focuses on building and providing MAA best practices to help prevent, detect, tolerate and repair from all outages and provide a highly available, reliable and scalable solutions for all platforms. Since most of our projects are done on Exadata and  Exadata Cloud, MAA best practices on Exadata and Exadata Cloud tend to be more optimized and integrated than any other platform. We work closely with different development teams to enhance Oracle's overall Exadata, ZDLRA and MAA solutions. We also consult with strategic external and internal customers on HA architectures, features and solutions; however the MAA OTN website is our single external customer portal that contains our MAA documentation, customer case studies and best practices papers. Please refer to MAA OTN website: http://www.oracle.com/goto/maa

The MAA solutions showcase a tight integration of our HA features, providing zero to minimal downtime for planned and unplanned outages while maximizing the ROI and Quality of Service for customers. Some of our projects involve hot patching and rolling upgrades with Oracle clusterware, ASM, Real Application Cluster, Active Data Guard and GoldenGate. We also provide solutions showcasing the fastest repair using Exadata, ASM, RAC, Active Data Guard, RMAN, GoldenGate and Flashback Technologies for example.

Key Areas of Responsibility:
* Generic MAA Architecture for DBaaS and all databases (Bronze, Silver, Gold, Platinum blueprints), HA configuration and operational practices
* Exadata and Exadata Cloud Best Practices 
* ZDLRA MAA best practices
* Cloud MAA best practices including architecture, configuration and life cycle operational practices
